df['year'] = df['date'].dt.year
df['month'] = df['date'].dt.month
df['day_of_week'] = df['date'].dt.dayofweek
df['quarter'] = df['date'].dt.quarter

# Now set date as index
df.set_index('date', inplace=True)

# Seasonal decomposition
# We'll use a subset of recent data for clearer visualization
recent_years = df['adj_close'].iloc[-1825:]  # Last 5 years
decomposition = seasonal_decompose(recent_years, model='multiplicative', period=252)  # ~252 trading days in a year

fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(16, 12))
decomposition.observed.plot(ax=ax1)
ax1.set_title('Observed')
decomposition.trend.plot(ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title('Trend')
decomposition.seasonal.plot(ax=ax3)
ax3.set_title('Seasonality')
decomposition.resid.plot(ax=ax4)
ax4.set_title('Residuals')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('amazon_seasonal_decomposition.png')
plt.show()

PART 2: FEATURE ENGINEERING¶

print("\n=== PART 2: FEATURE ENGINEERING ===")

# Create a copy of the original dataframe
df_fe = df.copy()

# Technical Indicators

# 1. Moving Averages
df_fe['MA10'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=10).mean()
df_fe['MA30'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=30).mean()
df_fe['MA50'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=50).mean()
df_fe['MA200'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=200).mean()

# Plot Moving Averages
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['adj_close'], label='Adjusted Close', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MA10'], label='10-day MA')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MA30'], label='30-day MA')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MA50'], label='50-day MA')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MA200'], label='200-day MA')
plt.title('Amazon Stock Price with Moving Averages')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price (USD)')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig('amazon_moving_averages.png')
plt.show()

# 2. Relative Strength Index (RSI)
# Calculate RSI 14-period
delta = df_fe['adj_close'].diff()
gain = (delta.where(delta > 0, 0)).rolling(window=14).mean()
loss = (-delta.where(delta < 0, 0)).rolling(window=14).mean()
rs = gain / loss
df_fe['RSI'] = 100 - (100 / (1 + rs))

# 3. MACD (Moving Average Convergence Divergence)
df_fe['EMA12'] = df_fe['adj_close'].ewm(span=12, adjust=False).mean()
df_fe['EMA26'] = df_fe['adj_close'].ewm(span=26, adjust=False).mean()
df_fe['MACD'] = df_fe['EMA12'] - df_fe['EMA26']
df_fe['MACD_signal'] = df_fe['MACD'].ewm(span=9, adjust=False).mean()
df_fe['MACD_hist'] = df_fe['MACD'] - df_fe['MACD_signal']

# Plot MACD
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['adj_close'], label='Adjusted Close')
plt.title('Amazon Stock Price and MACD')
plt.ylabel('Price (USD)')
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MACD'], label='MACD')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MACD_signal'], label='Signal Line')
plt.bar(df_fe.index, df_fe['MACD_hist'], label='MACD Histogram')
plt.ylabel('MACD')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig('amazon_macd.png')
plt.show()

# 4. Bollinger Bands
df_fe['MA20'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=20).mean()
df_fe['20d_std'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=20).std()
df_fe['upper_band'] = df_fe['MA20'] + (df_fe['20d_std'] * 2)
df_fe['lower_band'] = df_fe['MA20'] - (df_fe['20d_std'] * 2)

# Plot Bollinger Bands
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['adj_close'], label='Adjusted Close')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['MA20'], label='20-day MA')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['upper_band'], label='Upper Band')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['lower_band'], label='Lower Band')
plt.fill_between(df_fe.index, df_fe['upper_band'], df_fe['lower_band'], alpha=0.1)
plt.title('Amazon Stock Price with Bollinger Bands')
plt.ylabel('Price (USD)')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig('amazon_bollinger_bands.png')
plt.show()

# 5. Average True Range (ATR) - Volatility indicator
high_low = df_fe['high'] - df_fe['low']
high_close = np.abs(df_fe['high'] - df_fe['close'].shift())
low_close = np.abs(df_fe['low'] - df_fe['close'].shift())
ranges = pd.concat([high_low, high_close, low_close], axis=1)
true_range = np.max(ranges, axis=1)
df_fe['ATR'] = true_range.rolling(14).mean()

# 6. On-Balance Volume (OBV)
df_fe['OBV'] = np.where(df_fe['close'] > df_fe['close'].shift(), 
                       df_fe['volume'], 
                       np.where(df_fe['close'] < df_fe['close'].shift(), 
                               -df_fe['volume'], 0)).cumsum()

# 7. Stochastic Oscillator
df_fe['14-high'] = df_fe['high'].rolling(14).max()
df_fe['14-low'] = df_fe['low'].rolling(14).min()
df_fe['%K'] = (df_fe['close'] - df_fe['14-low'])*100/(df_fe['14-high'] - df_fe['14-low'])
df_fe['%D'] = df_fe['%K'].rolling(3).mean()

# 8. Rate of Change (ROC)
df_fe['ROC'] = ((df_fe['close'] / df_fe['close'].shift(10)) - 1) * 100

# 9. Price difference features
df_fe['price_diff'] = df_fe['close'] - df_fe['open']
df_fe['price_diff_pct'] = ((df_fe['close'] - df_fe['open']) / df_fe['open']) * 100

# 10. Lag features for time series prediction
for i in [1, 2, 3, 5, 10, 21, 63, 126, 252]:
    df_fe[f'adj_close_lag_{i}'] = df_fe['adj_close'].shift(i)
    df_fe[f'return_lag_{i}'] = df_fe['daily_return'].shift(i)

# 11. Rolling window statistics
df_fe['rolling_mean_5d'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=5).mean()
df_fe['rolling_std_5d'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=5).std()
df_fe['rolling_min_5d'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=5).min()
df_fe['rolling_max_5d'] = df_fe['adj_close'].rolling(window=5).max()

# 12. Rolling window return statistics
df_fe['rolling_mean_return_5d'] = df_fe['daily_return'].rolling(window=5).mean()
df_fe['rolling_std_return_5d'] = df_fe['daily_return'].rolling(window=5).std()

# 13. Normalized price features
price_min = df_fe['adj_close'].min()
price_max = df_fe['adj_close'].max()
df_fe['adj_close_norm'] = (df_fe['adj_close'] - price_min) / (price_max - price_min)

# 14. Price momentum features
df_fe['momentum_1m'] = df_fe['adj_close'] / df_fe['adj_close'].shift(21) - 1
df_fe['momentum_3m'] = df_fe['adj_close'] / df_fe['adj_close'].shift(63) - 1
df_fe['momentum_6m'] = df_fe['adj_close'] / df_fe['adj_close'].shift(126) - 1
df_fe['momentum_12m'] = df_fe['adj_close'] / df_fe['adj_close'].shift(252) - 1

# 15. Gap features
df_fe['gap_open'] = df_fe['open'] / df_fe['close'].shift(1) - 1
df_fe['gap_close'] = df_fe['close'] / df_fe['open'] - 1

# 16. Moving average crossover signals
df_fe['ma_crossover_signal'] = np.where(df_fe['MA10'] > df_fe['MA30'], 1, 0)

# 17. RSI categories
df_fe['RSI_oversold'] = np.where(df_fe['RSI'] < 30, 1, 0)
df_fe['RSI_overbought'] = np.where(df_fe['RSI'] > 70, 1, 0)

# Display column names for the fully-featured dataset
print("Available features after engineering:")
print(df_fe.columns.tolist())

# Print shape after feature engineering
print(f"\nDataset shape after feature engineering: {df_fe.shape}")

# Save the feature-engineered dataset
df_fe.to_csv('amazon_stock_with_features.csv')

# Plot a few key engineered features
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 20))

plt.subplot(5, 1, 1)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['RSI'])
plt.axhline(y=70, color='r', linestyle='-', alpha=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=30, color='g', linestyle='-', alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Relative Strength Index (RSI)')
plt.ylabel('RSI')

plt.subplot(5, 1, 2)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['momentum_1m'], label='1-month')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['momentum_3m'], label='3-month')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['momentum_6m'], label='6-month')
plt.title('Price Momentum')
plt.ylabel('Momentum')
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(5, 1, 3)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['ATR'])
plt.title('Average True Range (ATR)')
plt.ylabel('ATR')

plt.subplot(5, 1, 4)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['%K'], label='%K')
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['%D'], label='%D')
plt.title('Stochastic Oscillator')
plt.ylabel('Value')
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(5, 1, 5)
plt.plot(df_fe.index, df_fe['rolling_std_return_5d'])
plt.title('5-Day Rolling Standard Deviation of Returns')
plt.ylabel('Standard Deviation')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('amazon_engineered_features.png')
plt.show()

print("\nFeature engineering completed successfully!")

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller, acf, pacf
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
import pmdarima as pm
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score
from math import sqrt


# Let's shorten the forecast horizon to improve accuracy
# We'll use 30 trading days (~ 1.5 months) instead of a full year
forecast_horizon = 30

# Define the train-test split
# Use the last forecast_horizon days for testing
train = df.iloc[:-forecast_horizon]
test = df.iloc[-forecast_horizon:]

print(f"Training set size: {train.shape}")
print(f"Test set period: {test.index.min()} to {test.index.max()} ({len(test)} days)")

# Extract target variable series
y_train = train['adj_close']
y_test = test['adj_close']

# Define function to evaluate models
def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    """Evaluate model performance with multiple metrics"""
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    rmse = sqrt(mse)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    
    # Calculate percentage errors
    mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100
    
    # R-squared can be negative if model is worse than mean
    r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    
    print(f"{model_name} Performance Metrics:")
    print(f"MSE: {mse:.2f}")
    print(f"RMSE: {rmse:.2f}")
    print(f"MAE: {mae:.2f}")
    print(f"MAPE: {mape:.2f}%")
    print(f"R: {r2:.4f}")
    
    return {
        'model': model_name,
        'mse': mse, 
        'rmse': rmse, 
        'mae': mae, 
        'mape': mape,
        'r2': r2
    }

# Function to plot predictions vs actual
def plot_predictions(y_test, predictions, model_name, error_metrics=None):
    """Plot test data against predictions"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.plot(y_test.index, y_test.values, label='Actual', color='blue', linewidth=2)
    plt.plot(y_test.index, predictions, label=f'{model_name} Predictions', 
             color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
    
    # Add error band (10% of the actual value)
    plt.fill_between(
        y_test.index,
        y_test.values * 0.9,
        y_test.values * 1.1,
        color='blue', alpha=0.1, label='10% Error Band'
    )
    
    plt.title(f'Amazon Stock Price Prediction - {model_name}')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Adjusted Close Price (USD)')
    plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # Add metrics as text if provided
    if error_metrics:
        metrics_text = (
            f"RMSE: {error_metrics['rmse']:.2f}\n"
            f"MAE: {error_metrics['mae']:.2f}\n"
            f"MAPE: {error_metrics['mape']:.2f}%\n"
            f"R: {error_metrics['r2']:.4f}"
        )
        props = dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor='white', alpha=0.7)
        plt.text(0.02, 0.05, metrics_text, transform=plt.gca().transAxes, 
                 fontsize=9, verticalalignment='bottom', bbox=props)
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(f'amazon_prediction_{model_name.lower().replace(" ", "_")}.png')
    plt.show()

# Function to check stationarity with ADF test
def check_stationarity(series, window=12):
    """Check stationarity of a time series with ADF test and rolling statistics"""
    # Perform ADF test
    print("Results of Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test:")
    adf_result = adfuller(series.dropna())
    
    adf_output = pd.Series(
        adf_result[0:4], 
        index=['ADF Statistic', 'p-value', 'Lags Used', 'Number of Observations Used']
    )
    
    for key, value in adf_result[4].items():
        adf_output[f'Critical Value ({key})'] = value
    
    print(adf_output)
    
    # Interpret the results
    if adf_result[1] <= 0.05:
        print("Strong evidence against the null hypothesis")
        print("Reject the null hypothesis")
        print("Data is stationary")
        return True
    else:
        print("Weak evidence against the null hypothesis")
        print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis")
        print("Data is non-stationary")
        return False
    
    # Also plot rolling statistics for visual inspection
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    
    # Original series
    plt.subplot(3, 1, 1)
    plt.plot(series, label='Original Series')
    plt.title('Original Time Series and Rolling Statistics')
    plt.legend()
    
    # Rolling mean and std
    plt.subplot(3, 1, 2)
    rolling_mean = series.rolling(window=window).mean()
    rolling_std = series.rolling(window=window).std()
    plt.plot(rolling_mean, label='Rolling Mean')
    plt.plot(rolling_std, label='Rolling Std')
    plt.legend()
    
    # First difference 
    plt.subplot(3, 1, 3)
    plt.plot(series.diff().dropna(), label='First Difference')
    plt.title('First Difference of Series')
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('stationarity_check.png')
    plt.show()

# Check stationarity of our series
print("\nChecking stationarity of price series...")
is_stationary = check_stationarity(y_train)

# Determine if we need differencing
if not is_stationary:
    print("\nSeries is not stationary. Checking stationarity after differencing...")
    is_diff1_stationary = check_stationarity(y_train.diff().dropna())
    d_order = 1 if is_diff1_stationary else 2
    print(f"Using differencing order d={d_order} for models")
else:
    d_order = 0
    print("Series is stationary. No differencing needed.")

# Examine ACF and PACF to determine p, q orders
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.subplot(211)
plot_acf(y_train.diff(d_order).dropna(), ax=plt.gca(), lags=40)
plt.subplot(212)
plot_pacf(y_train.diff(d_order).dropna(), ax=plt.gca(), lags=40)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('acf_pacf_analysis.png')
plt.show()

print("\n=== MODELING TRADITIONAL TIME SERIES MODELS ===")

# Store results for comparison
model_results = []

# 1. Naive Model (Random Walk)
print("\n1. Fitting Naive Model (Random Walk)...")
# The prediction for each point is simply the previous value
naive_predictions = np.array([y_train.iloc[-1]] * len(y_test))
naive_metrics = evaluate_model(y_test, naive_predictions, "Naive")
model_results.append(naive_metrics)
plot_predictions(y_test, naive_predictions, "Naive", naive_metrics)

# 2. Seasonal Naive Model
print("\n2. Fitting Seasonal Naive Model...")
# Use the value from the same day of the previous week
# If we have less than a week of data before test, fall back to simple naive
if len(y_train) >= 5:  # Assuming 5 trading days in a week
    seasonal_period = 5  # Trading days in a week
    seasonal_indices = range(len(y_test))
    seasonal_naive_predictions = np.array([
        y_train.iloc[-(seasonal_period - i % seasonal_period)] 
        for i in seasonal_indices
    ])
    seasonal_naive_metrics = evaluate_model(y_test, seasonal_naive_predictions, "Seasonal Naive")
    model_results.append(seasonal_naive_metrics)
    plot_predictions(y_test, seasonal_naive_predictions, "Seasonal Naive", seasonal_naive_metrics)
else:
    print("Not enough historical data for seasonal naive model")

# 3. Simple Exponential Smoothing
print("\n3. Fitting Simple Exponential Smoothing Model...")
# Simple Exponential Smoothing works well when no trend or seasonality
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import SimpleExpSmoothing
ses_model = SimpleExpSmoothing(y_train).fit(optimized=True)
ses_predictions = ses_model.forecast(len(y_test))
ses_metrics = evaluate_model(y_test, ses_predictions, "Simple Exponential Smoothing")
model_results.append(ses_metrics)
plot_predictions(y_test, ses_predictions, "Simple Exponential Smoothing", ses_metrics)

# 4. Holt-Winters (Triple Exponential Smoothing)
print("\n4. Fitting Holt-Winters Model...")
# Holt-Winters handles both trend and seasonality
hw_model = ExponentialSmoothing(
    y_train, 
    trend='add',           # Can be 'add' or 'mul' for additive or multiplicative trend
    seasonal='add',        # Can be 'add' or 'mul' for additive or multiplicative seasonality
    seasonal_periods=5     # 5 days in a trading week
).fit(optimized=True)
hw_predictions = hw_model.forecast(len(y_test))
hw_metrics = evaluate_model(y_test, hw_predictions, "Holt-Winters")
model_results.append(hw_metrics)
plot_predictions(y_test, hw_predictions, "Holt-Winters", hw_metrics)

# 5. Auto ARIMA - Let the algorithm find the best parameters
print("\n5. Fitting Auto ARIMA Model...")
try:
    # Use auto_arima with a more comprehensive search
    auto_arima_model = pm.auto_arima(

        trace=True,
        error_action='ignore',
        suppress_warnings=True,
        stepwise=True,
        n_fits=50                 # Increase number of fits for better results
    )

    print(auto_arima_model.summary())
    
    # Make predictions
    arima_predictions = auto_arima_model.predict(n_periods=len(y_test))
    arima_metrics = evaluate_model(y_test, arima_predictions, "Auto ARIMA")
    model_results.append(arima_metrics)
    plot_predictions(y_test, arima_predictions, "Auto ARIMA", arima_metrics)
    
except Exception as e:

# 8. ARIMAX with exogenous variables (Add market trend as external factor)
print("\n8. Fitting ARIMAX Model with Moving Average as exogenous variable...")
try:
    # Create an exogenous variable: 10-day moving average
    # This can sometimes improve model performance
    ma10 = y_train.rolling(window=10).mean()
    ma10 = ma10.fillna(method='bfill')  # Backfill NA values
    
    # Convert to DataFrame for ARIMAX
    train_exog = pd.DataFrame({'ma10': ma10})
    
    # For test data, we need to create exogenous variables too
    # We'll use a simple approach of extending the last values
    # In a real application, you'd need a proper approach to forecast exog variables
    test_exog = pd.DataFrame(index=y_test.index)
    test_exog['ma10'] = np.array([train_exog['ma10'].iloc[-1]] * len(y_test))
    
    # Fit ARIMAX with exogenous variables
    arimax_model = SARIMAX(
        y_train,
        exog=train_exog,
        order=(1, 1, 1)
    ).fit(disp=False)
    
    print(arimax_model.summary())
    
    # Make predictions with exogenous variables
    arimax_predictions = arimax_model.forecast(steps=len(y_test), exog=test_exog)
    arimax_metrics = evaluate_model(y_test, arimax_predictions, "ARIMAX")
    model_results.append(arimax_metrics)
    plot_predictions(y_test, arimax_predictions, "ARIMAX", arimax_metrics)
    
except Exception as e:
